Test 1: Health Check
Bash

# Test ALB directly
curl http://YOUR-ALB-DNS/api/health

# Expected output (run multiple times to see different hosts):
{
  "status": "healthy",
  "host": "ip-10-0-1-123.ec2.internal",
  "uptime": 234.567,
  "timestamp": "2024-01-15T10:30:00.000Z"
}
Test 2: Load Balancing Verification
Bash

# Run this script to see round-robin distribution
for i in {1..10}; do
  curl -s http://YOUR-ALB-DNS/api/health | jq -r '.host'
done

# Output should show alternating hostnames:
# ip-10-0-1-123.ec2.internal
# ip-10-0-2-456.ec2.internal
# ip-10-0-1-123.ec2.internal
# ip-10-0-2-456.ec2.internal
Test 3: Frontend Access
Get Frontend Public IP:

EC2 → Instances → frontend-server → Copy Public IPv4 address
Open in browser:

text

http://YOUR-FRONTEND-PUBLIC-IP
Expected behavior:

React app loads
Server info shows backend instance details
Refresh page → hostname should change (load balancing!)
Add messages → see which instance handled the request
Test 4: Auto Scaling / Fault Tolerance
Stop one backend instance:

Bash

# AWS Console: EC2 → Instances → Select one backend → Instance state → Stop
Expected:

ALB marks instance as unhealthy
Traffic routes only to healthy instance
Auto Scaling Group launches a replacement (if min capacity = 2)
No downtime for users
Verify:

Bash

# Continue making requests - should still work
watch -n 1 'curl -s http://YOUR-ALB-DNS/api/health | jq'
